answer:
Let $x = \angle BAC.$  Then $\angle ABC = \angle ACB = 90^\circ - x,$ and $\angle BDC = 3x.$  Also, since $\angle BDC$ is exterior to $\triangle AMC,$
$$\angle BDC = \angle MAC + \angle ACM = 90^\circ - x + x = 90^\circ.$$Thus, $3x = 90^\circ,$ so $x = 30^\circ.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, M;

A = (0,11);
D = (0,1);
B = (-11/2,0);
C = (11/2,0);
M = (B + C)/2;

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--M);
draw(B--D--C);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, NW);
label("$M$", M, S);
label("$30^\circ$", A + (-1.1,-0.7), NE);
label("$30^\circ$", M + (-0.3,0.5), NW);
label("$30^\circ$", A + (-1.5,-1.5), NW);
label("$10$", A + (0,-1.5), W);
label("$11$", M + (0,0.4), W);
label("$11$", A + (-0.4,-0.8), W);
[/asy]

Let $BM = CM = x.$  Then $x^2 = 11^2 + (2x - 10)^2,$ so $x = 13.$  (We discard the solution $x = 25,$ as that would imply $AC < AM.$)

